//!
//! ## Background
//!
//! Rust 1.95 stabilized asynchronous closures (`async |x| ...`) and the corresponding `AsyncFn` trait family:
//! - `AsyncFn`: Can be called asynchronously multiple times (similar to `Fn`, but each call returns a `Future`)
//! - `AsyncFnMut`: Can be called asynchronously multiple times, but may modify captured state
//! - `AsyncFnOnce`: Can be called asynchronously only once, consuming ownership
//!
//! This is different from synchronous `Fn`/`FnMut`/`FnOnce`: asynchronous closures capture the state needed for the `Future` generated at invocation time, not the result of the invocation itself.
//!
//! ## Requirements
//!
//! - Use `impl AsyncFn` as a generic parameter bound
//! - Compare usage scenarios of `async fn` vs `AsyncFn` trait
//! - Understand capture semantics of asynchronous closures

